data.content:
**MSTest Collection Assertions**

Your test works but produces unhelpful failure messages (just "Assert.IsTrue failed"). MSTest has dedicated APIs for this:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** — on failure shows *both* values instead of just "false"
- **Add messages** to `Assert.IsTrue` so failures are diagnosable
- **`Assert.IsNotNull()`** is clearer than `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)`
- `users.Single()` already throws on missing/duplicate — use `Assert.IsTrue` + `Any()` or `Assert.IsNotNull` + `FirstOrDefault()` depending on your intent

**For richer collection assertions**, consider the `CollectionAssert` class:

```csharp
// Verify no nulls in the collection
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users.ToList());

// Verify all items satisfy a condition (via a helper list)
CollectionAssert.IsSubsetOf(expectedUsers, actualUsers.ToList());
```

> **Rule of thumb:** Prefer `Assert.AreEqual` over `Assert.IsTrue` whenever possible — it gives you the actual vs. expected values in the failure output.
